jects, the book develops the critical concept of the “sex life”—a colloquialism that opens up methodological avenues for understanding daily lived experience in granular detail, both in the distant past and today. Through this lens, Gamble explores how sex organized and permeated everyday life and experiences of gender and race in early modernity. He shows how affects around sex structure the plays of Shakespeare and his contemporaries, revealing the role of sexual feeling and sexual racism in early modern English drama.Sex Lives reshapes how we understand Renaissance literature, the history of sexuality, and the meaning of sex in both early modern Europe and our own moment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSex instructionxHistory. 0aSexxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aAs You LIke it.  aBritish European literature.  aGalatea.  aLGBT.  aMerchant of Venice.  aRenaissance.  aShakespeare.  aThe Island Princess.  aaffect.  acloset drama.  adisappointment.  aearly modern.  afeelings.  agender.  ahistory of sexuality.  aimagination.  ainstruction.  aknowledge.  alearning.  alived experience.  apersonal testimony.  apornography.  aproto-gay.  aqueer.  aromantic comedy.  asex life.  asexual affects.  asexual pedagogy.  asexual practice.  asexual racism.  asixteenth seventeenth century.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishz978311131918608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023z9783111318264oZDB-23-DSP08iTitle is part of eBo